---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import PageHeader from "../components/PageHeader.astro";
import SectionTitle from "../components/SectionTitle.astro";
import IconCardGrid from "../components/IconCardGrid.astro";

const pageTitle = "About RCAN | Returning Citizens Assistance Network";
const pageDescription =
  "Read about RCAN's mission, history, and community-centered approach to supporting successful re-entry.";

const motivationScriptures = [
  {
    text: `Continue to remember those in prison as if you were together with them in prison, and those who are mistreated as if you yourselves were suffering.`,
    reference: "Hebrews 13:3",
  },
  {
    text: `Suppose a brother or sister is without clothes and daily food. If one of you says to them, "Go in peace; keep warm and well fed," but does nothing about their physical needs, what good is it?`,
    reference: "James 2:14–16",
  },
  {
    text: `Whoever oppresses the poor shows contempt for their Maker, but whoever is kind to the needy honors God.`,
    reference: "Proverbs 14:31",
  },
  {
    text: `And what does the Lord require of you? To act justly and to love mercy and to walk humbly with your God.`,
    reference: "Micah 6:8",
  },
  {
    text: `Each of you should use whatever gift you have received to serve others, as faithful stewards of God's grace in its various forms.`,
    reference: "1 Peter 4:10",
  },
];

const values = [
  { icon: "hand-heart", label: "Dignity-first support for people returning to society" },
  { icon: "gift", label: "Rapid response to urgent short-term needs" },
  { icon: "users", label: "Congregation-led coordination and care" },
  { icon: "home", label: "Practical pathways toward housing, stability, and work" },
] as const;
---

<BaseLayout title={pageTitle} description={pageDescription}>
  <section aria-labelledby="about-heading" class="border-b border-border-default pb-10 pt-2 md:pb-12">
    <PageHeader
      id="about-heading"
      eyebrow="About RCAN"
      heading="Community networks changing reentry outcomes"
      subheading="Congregations across Washington, DC uniting to support returning citizens."
    />
  </section>

  <section aria-labelledby="history-heading" class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
    <SectionTitle id="history-heading" text="Our History" />
    <div class="mt-6 space-y-6 text-base leading-7 text-text-subtle">
      <p>
        RCAN traces its origins to 2015 and a presentation Bryan Stevenson of the Equal Justice
        Initiative gave at New York Avenue Presbyterian Church (NYAPC) in downtown Washington, DC.
        During his talk, Bryan urged the 750 people in attendance to "get proximate" to those who
        are or were incarcerated and become involved in their lives. Shortly after, Theo Brown, who
        had organized the program with Bryan, began meeting with other NYAPC members to discuss how
        they might respond to that challenge.
      </p>
      <div class="flex items-center justify-center gap-2" aria-hidden="true">
        <span class="h-px w-10 bg-border-default"></span>
        <span class="h-1 w-1 rounded-full bg-brand-secondary/60"></span>
        <span class="h-px w-10 bg-border-default"></span>
      </div>
      <p>
        As the group looked into ways they could help, Rob Hornstein of the DC Public Defender
        Service — who had also attended the talk — reached out to Theo with a proposal: PDS
        regularly worked with clients returning from incarceration who had almost no resources and
        needed help building a stable life in the community. NYAPC and PDS agreed to work together,
        and a partnership was born.
      </p>
      <div class="flex items-center justify-center gap-2" aria-hidden="true">
        <span class="h-px w-10 bg-border-default"></span>
        <span class="h-1 w-1 rounded-full bg-brand-secondary/60"></span>
        <span class="h-px w-10 bg-border-default"></span>
      </div>
      <p>
        At first, NYAPC fielded only one or two requests a month — furniture for an apartment, help
        with transportation, emergency food, or simply a friend. As referrals grew beyond what NYAPC
        could handle alone, Theo invited Don Craig and other leaders at nearby Metropolitan AME
        Church to help. After months of the two congregations working together, they decided to
        invite others to join. In 2018, NYAPC and Metropolitan AME wrote to about 20 congregations,
        inviting them to form the Returning Citizens Assistance Network. About a dozen signed on as
        founding members, and RCAN has grown steadily since — today, 21 churches and synagogues
        across Washington, DC work together to assist PDS clients who are returning from
        incarceration or still in prison.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section aria-labelledby="motivation-heading" class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
    <SectionTitle id="motivation-heading" text="Our Motivation" />
    <div class="mt-6 space-y-6 text-base leading-7 text-text-subtle">
      <p>
        The congregations that are part of RCAN are motivated by their shared spiritual conviction
        that each person is a child of God and deserves to be treated with respect and dignity.
        They are further motivated by commands from their faith traditions that urge followers to
        show particular concern for the needs of those who are marginalized in our society — the
        poor, the downtrodden, the despised, and those who are in prison.
      </p>
      <div class="flex items-center justify-center gap-2" aria-hidden="true">
        <span class="h-px w-10 bg-border-default"></span>
        <span class="h-1 w-1 rounded-full bg-brand-secondary/60"></span>
        <span class="h-px w-10 bg-border-default"></span>
      </div>
      <p>
        Scripture is filled with the admonition to treat others as we would like to be treated, and
        to take specific action to alleviate the suffering of those in physical and mental pain.
        Some of the passages that inspire RCAN members:
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-10 rounded-2xl border border-border-default/60 bg-surface-subtle px-6 py-8 md:px-10 md:py-10">
      <ul aria-label="Scriptures that inspire RCAN">
        {
          motivationScriptures.map((verse, index) => (
            <li class={index > 0 ? "mt-8" : ""}>
              {index > 0 && (
                <div class="mb-8 flex items-center justify-center gap-3" aria-hidden="true">
                  <span class="h-px w-16 bg-brand-secondary/25"></span>
                  <span class="h-2 w-2 rotate-45 bg-brand-secondary/60"></span>
                  <span class="h-px w-16 bg-brand-secondary/25"></span>
                </div>
              )}
              <figure>
                <blockquote class="font-serif text-lg italic leading-relaxed text-text-subtle">
                  <span aria-hidden="true" class="text-brand-secondary/50">&ldquo;</span>
                  {verse.text}
                  <span aria-hidden="true" class="text-brand-secondary/50">&rdquo;</span>
                </blockquote>
                <figcaption class="mt-2 text-right text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-brand-secondary/80">
                  {verse.reference}
                </figcaption>
              </figure>
            </li>
          ))
        }
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section aria-labelledby="approach-heading" class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
    <SectionTitle id="approach-heading" text="Our Approach" />
    <p class="mx-auto mt-6 max-w-2xl text-center text-base leading-7 text-text-subtle">
      RCAN is rooted in the conviction that practical support and faithful community can reshape
      reentry outcomes. Twenty-one congregations across Washington, DC share this commitment —
      different in tradition, united in purpose.
    </p>
    <IconCardGrid items={values} ariaLabel="RCAN core values" columns={4} />
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
